<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="463" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1436,1189,2006]" pageId="6" pageNumber="463">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,321,1225,1250]" pageId="6" pageNumber="463">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[330,491,1225,1249]" class="Insecta" family="Drilidae" genus="Drilus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="463" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bicolor">
<emphasis box="[330,491,1225,1249]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="463">Drilus bicolor</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is easily recognizable from its Levantine congeners by bicolored elytra, which are lighter only at humeri (
<figureCitation box="[421,491,1261,1286]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 6" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1879,1902]" captionTargetBox="[170,1419,200,1853]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[156,1430,195,1858]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 6. General appearance. 1 — Drilus adustus; 2 — D. akbesianus; 3 — D. bicolor; 4 — D. nemethi sp. nov.; 5 — D. rectus; 6 — D. rufipes. Scale 2.0 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/226484/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="463">
Fig. 
<number box="[476,491,1262,1286]" pageId="6" pageNumber="463" value="3.0">3</number>
</figureCitation>
), shorter antennomere 
<number box="[758,772,1262,1286]" pageId="6" pageNumber="463" value="3.0">3</number>
(
<figureCitation box="[790,861,1261,1286]" captionStart="FIGURES 7 – 18" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1576,1599]" captionTargetBox="[154,1423,199,1547]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[151,1436,193,1555]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 7 – 18. Antenna. 7 — Drilus adustus; 8 — D. akbesianus; 9 — D. bicolor; 10 — D. nemethi sp. nov.; 11 — D. rectus; 12 — D. rufipes. Pronotum. 13 — Drilus adustus; 14 — D. akbesianus; 15 — D. bicolor; 16 — D. nemethi sp. nov.; 17 — D. rectus; 18 — D. rufipes. Scale 1.0 mm (Figs 7 – 12), 0.5 mm (Figs 13 – 18)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/226485/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="463">
Fig. 
<number box="[845,861,1262,1286]" pageId="6" pageNumber="463" value="9.0">9</number>
</figureCitation>
), and pronotum with fine, deep puncturation, and acutely projected hind angles (
<figureCitation box="[493,577,1297,1322]" captionStart="FIGURES 7 – 18" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1576,1599]" captionTargetBox="[154,1423,199,1547]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[151,1436,193,1555]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 7 – 18. Antenna. 7 — Drilus adustus; 8 — D. akbesianus; 9 — D. bicolor; 10 — D. nemethi sp. nov.; 11 — D. rectus; 12 — D. rufipes. Pronotum. 13 — Drilus adustus; 14 — D. akbesianus; 15 — D. bicolor; 16 — D. nemethi sp. nov.; 17 — D. rectus; 18 — D. rufipes. Scale 1.0 mm (Figs 7 – 12), 0.5 mm (Figs 13 – 18)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/226485/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="463">
Fig. 
<number box="[546,577,1297,1322]" pageId="6" pageNumber="463" value="15.0">15</number>
</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="7" lastPageNumber="464" pageId="6" pageNumber="463" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1436,1189,2006]" pageId="6" pageNumber="463">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,372,1333,1358]" pageId="6" pageNumber="463">Redescription.</emphasis>
Male. Body medium-sized, elongate, 
<number box="[801,836,1334,1358]" pageId="6" pageNumber="463" value="3.1">3.1</number>
times as long as width at humeri, moderately convex dorsally (
<figureCitation box="[256,324,1369,1394]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 6" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1879,1902]" captionTargetBox="[170,1419,200,1853]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[156,1430,195,1858]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 6. General appearance. 1 — Drilus adustus; 2 — D. akbesianus; 3 — D. bicolor; 4 — D. nemethi sp. nov.; 5 — D. rectus; 6 — D. rufipes. Scale 2.0 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/226484/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="463">
Fig. 
<number box="[308,324,1370,1394]" pageId="6" pageNumber="463" value="3.0">3</number>
</figureCitation>
). All body parts yellowish to brown, only elytral apical four fifths dark brown; entire body covered with yellow pubescence.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1436,1189,2006]" pageId="6" pageNumber="463">
Head slightly hypognathous, including eyes as wide as anterior margin of pronotum. Surface of cranium punctured, wrinkled, dorsally with long sparse semierect pubescence. Eyes medium-sized, hemispherically prominent, their frontal distance 
<number box="[538,573,1514,1538]" pageId="6" pageNumber="463" value="2.1">2.1</number>
times eye diameter. Mandibles robust, long, considerably curved, incisor margin with conspicuous tooth in middle part, shiny. Maxillary palpi slender; apical palpomere obliquely cut; labial palpi tiny, apical palpomere pointed. Antennae 
<number box="[713,737,1585,1610]" pageId="6" pageNumber="463" value="11.0">11</number>
-segmented, reaching third of elytral length, scapus robust, pedicel short, small, antennomere 
<number box="[534,548,1622,1646]" pageId="6" pageNumber="463" value="3.0">3</number>
serrate, about 
<number box="[712,747,1621,1646]" pageId="6" pageNumber="463" value="2.5">2.5</number>
times longer than antennomere 
<number box="[1106,1122,1622,1646]" pageId="6" pageNumber="463" value="2.0">2</number>
, antennomeres 
<number box="[1295,1352,1622,1646]" pageId="6" pageNumber="463" value="7.0" valueMax="10.0" valueMin="4.0">4–10</number>
shortly flabellate, subequal in length, apical antennomere simple, longest, slightly longer than lamella of penultimate antennomere (
<figureCitation box="[311,379,1693,1718]" captionStart="FIGURES 7 – 18" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1576,1599]" captionTargetBox="[154,1423,199,1547]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[151,1436,193,1555]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 7 – 18. Antenna. 7 — Drilus adustus; 8 — D. akbesianus; 9 — D. bicolor; 10 — D. nemethi sp. nov.; 11 — D. rectus; 12 — D. rufipes. Pronotum. 13 — Drilus adustus; 14 — D. akbesianus; 15 — D. bicolor; 16 — D. nemethi sp. nov.; 17 — D. rectus; 18 — D. rufipes. Scale 1.0 mm (Figs 7 – 12), 0.5 mm (Figs 13 – 18)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/226485/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="463">
Fig. 
<number box="[363,379,1694,1718]" pageId="6" pageNumber="463" value="9.0">9</number>
</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1436,1189,2006]" lastBlockId="7.[151,1436,151,429]" lastPageId="7" lastPageNumber="464" pageId="6" pageNumber="463">
Pronotum flat, transverse, widest at basal margin, 
<number box="[766,801,1730,1754]" pageId="6" pageNumber="463" value="1.7">1.7</number>
times wider posteriorly than length at midline. Anterior margin straight, lateral margins convex, posterior margin slightly sinuate in middle. Anterior angles almost rectangular, posterior angles considerably prominent, acutely projected (
<figureCitation box="[1015,1106,1801,1826]" captionStart="FIGURES 7 – 18" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1576,1599]" captionTargetBox="[154,1423,199,1547]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[151,1436,193,1555]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 7 – 18. Antenna. 7 — Drilus adustus; 8 — D. akbesianus; 9 — D. bicolor; 10 — D. nemethi sp. nov.; 11 — D. rectus; 12 — D. rufipes. Pronotum. 13 — Drilus adustus; 14 — D. akbesianus; 15 — D. bicolor; 16 — D. nemethi sp. nov.; 17 — D. rectus; 18 — D. rufipes. Scale 1.0 mm (Figs 7 – 12), 0.5 mm (Figs 13 – 18)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/226485/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="463">
Fig. 
<number box="[1075,1106,1801,1826]" pageId="6" pageNumber="463" value="15.0">15</number>
</figureCitation>
); surface of disc with fine punctures, distributed sparsely in middle and densely at margins, with sparse, semierect, long setae. Scutellum flat, triangle-shaped. Prosternum transverse, prosternal process short, slightly elevated in middle part. Mesoventrite narrow, v-shaped. Metaventrite large, trapezoidal, sparsely punctured. Elytra subparallel-sided, slightly widened between humeri and half of elytral length, 
<number box="[644,679,1945,1970]" pageId="6" pageNumber="463" value="2.5">2.5</number>
times longer than width at humeri, tapered apically, covered with sparse, semierect pubescence. Abdomen slender, ventrites with fine microstructure and sparse, long hairs. Legs slender, slightly compressed, with sparse, long, semierect setae, coxae long, robust, trochanters slender, obliquely attached to femora, tarsomeres 
<number box="[507,549,188,212]" pageId="7" pageNumber="464" value="2.0" valueMax="3.0" valueMin="1.0">1–3</number>
subequal in length, tarsomere 
<number box="[899,913,188,212]" pageId="7" pageNumber="464" value="4.0">4</number>
shortest, apical tarsomere long, claws simple, slightly curved.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1436,151,429]" pageId="7" pageNumber="464">
Male genitalia with robust phallus; phallus longer than paramerae, considerably curved; short robust paramerae with sparse setae; phallobase long (
<figureCitation box="[671,754,295,320]" captionStart="FIGURES 19 – 24" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1605,1628]" captionTargetBox="[162,1421,342,1577]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[151,1436,337,1584]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 19 – 24. Male genitalia. 19 — Drilus adustus; 20 — D. akbesianus; 21 — D. bicolor; 22 — D. nemethi sp. nov.; 23 — D. rectus; 24 — D. rufipes. Scale 0.25 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/226486/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="464">
Fig. 
<number box="[723,754,296,320]" pageId="7" pageNumber="464" value="21.0">21</number>
</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
